---
---
<section id="protocol" class="py-24 border-t border-white/5">
  <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] muted font-semibold mb-3">The hard parts, answered</div>
    <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold tracking-tight mb-5 max-w-4xl">
      Protocol guarantees, <span class="gradient-text">not vibes.</span>
    </h2>
    <p class="text-lg muted leading-relaxed mb-12 max-w-3xl">
      The questions any serious engineer attacks first: what happens when a value contains the delimiter, what happens when the LLM emits the wrong number of columns, and how does the parser preserve order across a million rows. All three are spec-defined, all three are tested in the conformance suite.
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      <!-- Escaping -->
      <div class="glass rounded-2xl p-6">
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between mb-3 gap-3">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink-100">Delimiter escaping</h3>
          <span class="text-xs text-mint-400 font-mono uppercase tracking-wider">Spec rule §3.4</span>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
          A literal pipe inside a value is escaped with a backslash. The reference parser un-escapes during column split, so the value <code class="text-accent-300 bg-black/30 px-1 rounded text-xs">Suman | CEO</code> round-trips correctly without inflating column count.
        </p>
        <pre class="code-block !text-[0.78rem] leading-relaxed mb-3"><code><span class="muted"># Source value</span>
"Suman | CEO"

<span class="muted"># On the wire</span>
V|hire|Acme|Suman \| CEO|...

<span class="muted"># After ashru.parse(...)</span>
verb.karma == "Suman | CEO"   <span class="text-mint-400">✓</span></code></pre>
        <p class="text-xs muted leading-relaxed">Escape cost: 1 character per pipe. Fields containing pipes are rare in practice (titles, IDs); kāraka role values almost never collide with the delimiter.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Column count tolerance -->
      <div class="glass rounded-2xl p-6" style="border-color: rgba(139, 92, 246, 0.3); background: rgba(139, 92, 246, 0.04);">
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between mb-3 gap-3">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-ink-100">Wrong column count</h3>
          <span class="text-xs text-mint-400 font-mono uppercase tracking-wider">Spec rule §4.2</span>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
          If a row has fewer or more than the 10 V-columns, the reference parser logs the row to a warnings list and skips it. The document does not crash. This is intentional — at million-row scale, one drift-by-one row should not lose the entire batch.
        </p>
        <pre class="code-block !text-[0.78rem] leading-relaxed mb-3"><code><span class="muted"># Hallucinated 9-column row</span>
V|buy|Suman|Tesla|$60000||John|SF|p

<span class="muted"># Parser behaviour</span>
doc = ashru.parse(text)
len(doc.verbs)         <span class="muted"># good rows only</span>
len(doc.warnings)      <span class="muted"># 1: bad column count</span>
doc.warnings[0].line   <span class="muted"># source line number</span></code></pre>
        <p class="text-xs muted leading-relaxed">Strict mode (<code class="text-accent-300 bg-black/30 px-1 rounded text-xs">parse(..., strict=True)</code>) raises on the first bad row — opt in if you need fail-fast batch semantics.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- NEW: Parsing order guarantees (answers Joshna akka's question) -->
    <div class="glass-strong rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 mt-4" style="border-color: rgba(52, 211, 153, 0.25);">
      <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between mb-4 gap-3">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-ink-100">Parsing order — three guarantees</h3>
        <span class="text-xs text-mint-400 font-mono uppercase tracking-wider">Spec rules §3.1 · §3.2 · §3.3</span>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm muted leading-relaxed mb-5">
        At a million rows, the question that matters more than column count is order — does the parser preserve column order, row order, and context order, deterministically, every time? Yes, on all three. Here's exactly how:
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-5">
        <div class="rounded-xl p-5 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02]">
          <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-mint-400 font-mono mb-2">Order #1</div>
          <h4 class="text-base font-bold text-ink-100 mb-2">Column order — fixed positionally</h4>
          <p class="text-xs muted leading-relaxed">
            The 10 V-columns are defined in <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">SPEC.md</code>:
            verb · kartā · karma · karaṇa · sampradāna · apādāna · adhikaraṇa · tense · negated · attributes,
            in that exact sequence. The LLM gets this in the prompt; the parser splits on <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">|</code> and assigns by index.
            <strong class="text-ink-100">No auto-detection.</strong> A swapped column is data corruption — strict mode raises immediately.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-xl p-5 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02]">
          <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-mint-400 font-mono mb-2">Order #2</div>
          <h4 class="text-base font-bold text-ink-100 mb-2">Row order — linear stream</h4>
          <p class="text-xs muted leading-relaxed">
            Rows arrive top-to-bottom and are emitted in input order, deterministically.
            <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">F|</code> (file marker) and <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">S|</code> (sphere marker) lines apply forward to all subsequent V| rows
            until the next marker resets context. <strong class="text-ink-100">Same input → same output, every time.</strong>
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-xl p-5 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02]">
          <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] text-mint-400 font-mono mb-2">Order #3</div>
          <h4 class="text-base font-bold text-ink-100 mb-2">Context order — markers cascade</h4>
          <p class="text-xs muted leading-relaxed">
            The parser maintains a marker stack. Nested <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">F|</code> inside <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">S|</code> applies both to subsequent rows.
            Context never silently reorders or drops between rows. Predictable across million-row streams.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="rounded-xl p-5 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.02]">
        <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] muted font-semibold mb-3">Enforcement is binary, not ambiguous</div>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 text-sm">
          <div>
            <div class="font-mono text-flame-300 text-xs mb-1">strict=True</div>
            <p class="muted leading-relaxed">Raises <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">ValueError</code> on the first malformed row (wrong column count, unknown header, malformed escape). <strong class="text-ink-100">No data flows.</strong> Pick this for batch jobs where one corrupted row should fail the whole job.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="font-mono text-mint-400 text-xs mb-1">strict=False (default)</div>
            <p class="muted leading-relaxed">Logs a warning, skips the row, document survives. Pick this for streaming pipelines where one bad LLM output shouldn't kill a million-row batch. Bad rows are surfaced via <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">doc.warnings</code>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Conformance + spec coverage -->
    <div class="glass-strong rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-7 mt-4">
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 text-sm">
        <div>
          <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] muted font-semibold mb-2">Conformance suite</div>
          <p class="muted leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="text-mint-400">24/24 cases passing</strong> in <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">tests/v1.0/conformance.json</code> across both reference parsers — escape round-trips, column-count drift, malformed strict-mode, multi-sphere routing, file context, comments, attributes, bad-header rejection. Tested, not hoped for.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] muted font-semibold mb-2">Spec coverage (v1.0)</div>
          <p class="muted leading-relaxed">10-column V grammar · F-line file context · S-line sphere context · comments (<code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">#</code>) · blank-line tolerance · UTF-8 · escaping (<code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">\|</code>, <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">\\</code>, <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">\n</code>) · parser warnings contract · <code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">strict=True</code> mode.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] muted font-semibold mb-2">Reference parsers</div>
          <p class="muted leading-relaxed">Python (<code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">pip install ashru</code> · this week) and JavaScript (<code class="text-accent-300 text-xs">npm install @ashru/parser</code> · this week). ~250 LOC each, zero runtime dependencies, MIT.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
